TIME AND SPACE COMPLEXITY — COMPLETE THEORY NOTES

1.  What is Time Complexity? Time complexity tells you how fast your
    algorithm runs when input size (n) increases. It measures growth
    rate, not actual seconds.

2.  Why Big‑O Notation?

-   Shows worst‑case performance
-   Shows how code scales
-   Easy algorithm comparison
-   Big-O tells us how fast or slow an algorithm grows when the input size (n) becomes very large.
-   It shows the worst-case time or space an algorithm will take.

3.  Common Time Complexities O(1) — Constant
    Example: Accessing arr[i], HashMap get/put.

O(log n) — Logarithmic
Example: Binary search.

O(n) — Linear
Example: Single loop.

O(n log n) — Linearithmic
Example: Merge sort, heap sort.

O(n²) — Quadratic
Example: Nested loops, bubble sort.

O(n³) — Cubic
Example: Triple nested loops.

O(2ⁿ) — Exponential
Example: Fibonacci recursion without DP.

O(n!) — Factorial
Example: Permutation generation.

SPACE COMPLEXITY

Space complexity measures extra memory used by an algorithm.

1.  O(1) Space
    Example: Two‑pointer, in‑place sorting.

2.  O(n) Space
    Example: Arrays, BFS queue.

3.  O(log n) Space
    Example: Balanced tree recursion, binary search recursion.

4.  O(n²) Space
    Example: 2D DP tables.

Best, Worst & Average Case Best case: Minimum steps
Worst case: Maximum steps
Average case: Expected steps

How to Calculate Time Complexity - Ignore constants - Take highest order
term - Loops rule: Single loop → O(n)
Nested loops → Multiply
Consecutive loops → Add

Recursion Time Complexity T(n) = T(n‑1) + O(1) → O(n)
T(n) = 2T(n/2) + O(1) → O(n)
T(n) = T(n‑1) + T(n‑2) → O(2ⁿ)

Recursion Space Complexity Equal to recursion depth: Fibonacci recursion
→ O(n)
Binary search recursion → O(log n)

Big‑O Cheatsheet O(1) — Constant
O(log n) — Logarithmic
O(n) — Linear
O(n log n) — Linearithmic
O(n²) — Quadratic
O(2ⁿ) — Exponential
O(n!) — Factorial
